","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","Kilmanock,Ayrshire,Scotland.":"Ayrshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1250–":"about 1250–Deceased","1272–1333":"1272–1333","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","about 1250":"about 1250","1333":"1333","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","Kilmanock,Ayrshire,Scotland.":"Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Boyd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the island of Bute in the Firth of Clyde, from <i>Bòid</i> (genitive case of <i>Bòd</i>, the Gaelic name of the island of Bute) or <i>Bòideach</i>, denoting a person from Bute. Alternatively, the name may denote descendants of a <i>Gilla filius Boed</i>, who appears in reference to Glasgow Cathedral in the early 12th century, perhaps from the Gaelic personal name <i>Boite</i>, of uncertain origin.","Scottish and Irish: from the Gaelic epithet <i>buidhe</i> ‘yellow(-haired)’. Compare   Bowie  .","Manx: from <b>Mac Gille Buidhe</b> ‘son of the yellow-haired lad’ (compare 2 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bowie","meanings":["Scottish: from Gaelic <i>buidhe</i> ‘yellow’, i.e. ‘yellow-haired’, pronounced as two syllables. The equivalent term in Ireland is <i>buí</i>, often Anglicized as <i>boy</i>. The surname may also be a shortened form of   Gilboy  .","Irish: Anglicized form of <b>Ó Buadhaigh</b> (see   Bogue  )."]},{"name":"Boyde","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): variant of   Boyd  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lord Robert V Boyd was born about 1250, in Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1250–":"umbes 1250–Surnud","1272–1333":"1272–1333","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","about 1250":"umbes 1250","1333":"1333","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","Kilmanock,Ayrshire,Scotland.":"Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1250–":"noin 1250–Kuollut","1272–1333":"1272–1333","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","about 1250":"noin 1250","1333":"1333","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","Kilmanock,Ayrshire,Scotland.":"Ayrshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1250–":"environ 1250–Décédé","1272–1333":"1272–1333","1250–Male":"1250–Décédé","about 1250":"environ 1250","1333":"1333","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","Kilmanock,Ayrshire,Scotland.":"Ayrshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lord Robert V Boyd est né environ 1250, à Ayrshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"about 1250–":"um 1250–Verstorben","1272–1333":"1272–1333","1250–Male":"1250–Verstorben","about 1250":"um 1250","1333":"1333","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","Kilmanock,Ayrshire,Scotland.":"Ayrshire, Schottland, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Lord Robert V Boyd wurde um 1250 in Ayrshire, Schottland, United Kingdom geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"about 1250–":"about 1250–Desede","1272–1333":"1272–1333","1250–Male":"1250–Desede","about 1250":"about 1250","1333":"1333","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","Kilmanock,Ayrshire,Scotland.":"Ayrshire, Ecosse, 